  "context": "A pair of scissors is a hand-operated tool used for cutting paper, card, and sometimes metal. Scissors are often used for craft activities and fabric cutting. Scissors consist of a pair of metal blades pivoted so that the sharpened edges slide past each other when the handles opposite to the pivot are closed. Scissors are made in many forms for specialized uses. Hair-cutting shears and kitchen shears are functionally equivalent to scissors, and often their blades are serrated or scalloped, or even hooked, as is the case with barbers' shears used for cutting hair or (especially) beards. The largest scissors in the world are used in the timber industry for cutting wood.[1][2] Scissors are sometimes used without the user's fingers in between the two blades. Large shears used in the textile industry are also considered scissors. Hair shears resemble scissors, but are not considered scissors.[3] Operating scissors requires a combination of thumb and finger, depending on the design of the handles. The mechanism of scissors employs leverage and shear strength. The user holds one handle stationary while the other moves, applying a downward force which, when combined with the leverage of the blades, cuts the material between the blades. Scissors may be designed for right-handed or left-handed use depending on the location of the pivot. Scissors are classified as either pivot or compound. With pivot scissors, the blades are pivoted at the bottom, and the handles move in the same plane. With compound scissors, the handles move on separate axes, often in a scissor-like motion.
